 Kingdom|civil}}).<ref name=JH>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3211.html |title=John Holt |publisher=Uboat |date=16 February 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Ship|HMS ML|387}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[Fairmile B motor launch]] was sunk by an internal explosion at Beirut, Syria.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/14555.html |title=HMS ML 387 of the Royal Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-366||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Arctic Ocean]] north west of [[Hammerfest]], Norway ({{coord|72|10|N|14|44|E}}) by a [[Fairey Swordfish]] aircraft of [[816 Naval Air Squadron|816 Squadron]], [[Fleet Air Arm]] based on {{HMS|Chaser|D32|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 50 crew.<ref name=U366>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u366.htm |title=U-366 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=18 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German warship|UJ 1703|MOB-FD 63|2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The MOB-FD-class naval trawler/submarine chaser was torpedoed and sunk by Allied aircraft off [[Lindesnes]], Norway.<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=6115452|shipname=Uj.1703 |accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 March==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 March 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Ship|Japanese transport|America Maru||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The transport was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|420|nmi|km}} north north west of [[Saipan]] ({{coord|22|19|N|143|54|E}}) by {{USS|Nautilus|SS-168|6}} ({{navy|United States|1912}}). Five hundred and ninety-nine passengers and crew were killed. There were 43 survivors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/America_t.htm |title=Japanese Army Auxiliary Transports|publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Daniel Chester French||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Liberty ship]] struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off [[Bizerta]], [[French Algeria|Algeria]] ({{coord|37|17|N|10|22|W}}). 24 troops, 4 gunners and 9 crewmen killed. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Charon|W109|6}} ({{navy|UK}}), ''Thelma'' ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) and {{ship|ST|Rescue|1904|2}} ({{flagicon|UK|civil}} [[Gibraltar]]).<ref name=LibD>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibshipsD.html |title=Liberty Ships - D |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Rabe||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] off [[Obrestad]], Norway by an air attack.<ref name=seekrieg194403/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/wardiarygermann551944germ/page/90 |title=German Naval War Diary |publisher=archive.org |accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-744||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|52|01|N|22|37|W}}) by {{HMCS|Chaudiere|H99|6}}, {{HMCS|Chilliwack|K131|6}}, {{HMCS|Fennel|K194|6}}, {{HMCS|Gatineau|H61|6}}, {{HMCS|St. Catharines|K325|6}} (all {{navy|Canada|1911}}), {{HMS|Icarus|D03|6}} and {{HMS|Kenilworth Castle|K42|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}) with the loss of twelve of her 52 crew.<ref name=U744>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u744.htm |title=U-744 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=18 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-973||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was sunk in the [[Norwegian Sea]] ({{coord|70|40|N|5|48|E}}) by a [[Fairey Swordfish]] aircraft of [[816 Naval Air Squadron|816 Squadron]] [[Fleet Air Arm]] based on {{HMS|Chaser|D32|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of 51 of her 66 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 1304 Eisenach||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Vorpostenboot]]'' was sunk in the North Sea off [[IJmuiden]], [[North Holland]], Netherlands by {{ship|HMMTB|224}}, {{ship|HMMTB|225}}, {{ship|HMMTB|232}}, {{ship|HMMTB|234}}, {{ship|HMMTB|241}} and {{ship|HMMTB|244}} (all {{navy|UK}}). There were 20 dead and 19 missing.<ref name=V1304>{{cite web |url=http://wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?58845 |title=V-1304 (Eisenach) (+1944) |publisher=Wrecksite |accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/wardiarygermann551944germ/page/88 |title=German Naval War Diary |publisher=archive.org |accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Virginia Dare||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Liberty ship]] struck a mine in the Mediterranean Sea off [[Tunis]], [[French Tunisia|Tunisia]]. She was declared a total loss.<ref name=seekrieg194403/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==7 March==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=7 March 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Charlotte|1930|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship struck a [[naval mine|mine]] (probably German) and sank in the [[Black Sea]] off Cape Lukul. One crewman was lost.<ref name=seekrieg194403/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/wardiarygermann551944germ/page/112 |title=German Naval War Diary |publisher=archive.org |accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Juyo Maru||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a mine and a sank in the [[Indian Ocean]] off [[Koh Chang]], Thailand.<ref name=seekrieg194403/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS