n section to [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]], Canada, where she was subsequently used as a [[depot ship]].<ref name=JRP>{{cite web |url=https://novascotia.ca/museum/wrecks/wrecks/shipwrecks.asp?ID=2462 |title=Joel R. Poinsett - 1944 |publisher=Maritime Museum of the Atlantic |accessdate=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCA (HR) 672}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[Landing craft assault|landing craft assault (hedgerow)]] foundered off eastern [[Scotland]] during exercises.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite web |url= http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcalcsm.htm |title=LCA Assault Landing Craft and LCS(M) Support Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Naval-history.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW2BritishLossesbyDate3.htm |title=Royal Navy vessels lost at sea Jan. '44-Nov. 45 |publisher=Naval-history.net |accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCA (HR) 811}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[Landing craft assault|landing craft assault (hedgerow)]] foundered off eastern [[Scotland]] during exercises.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite web |url= http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcalcsm.htm |title=LCA Assault Landing Craft and LCS(M) Support Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Naval-history.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW2BritishLossesbyDate3.htm |title=Royal Navy vessels lost at sea Jan. '44-Nov. 45 |publisher=Naval-history.net |accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LST 362}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: [[Convoy MKS 40]]: The [[landing ship tank]] was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|48|00|N|17|23|W}}) by {{GS|U-744||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). 15 crew and 73 British troops were killed. There were 92 survivors.<ref name=LST342>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3208.html |title=HMS LST-362 |publisher=uboat.net |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese oiler|Naruto||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''Shiretoko''-class oiler was sunk by a bomb hit in the engine room in an air attack in [[Karavia Bay]], Rabaul, New Guinea. Raised September 1945. Beached in [[Keravia Bay]] on 26 October 1945. Refloated in 1958 and towed to [[Singapore]] where the vessel was abandoned. Probably scrapped later.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mBpF94zRT28C&pg=PA146&lpg=PA146&dq=Shinko+maru+No.+2,+1945&source=bl&ots=tYsPhTm_Md&sig=ACfU3U0uq3T5KzKRrr92qNQR0T_JB-v05w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjCp-WpkeLhAhUFXa0KHRQJDyE4ChDoATAJegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=Shinko%20maru%20No.%202%2C%201945&f=false |title=Rabaul's forgotten fleet |publisher=googlebooks |accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Naruto2_t.htm |title=Japanese Oilers |publisher=combinedfleet |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Shinkyo Maru||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] by {{USS|Picuda|SS-382|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194403/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Thor|1922|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk off [[Stad (peninsula)|Stad]], Norway by {{HMS|Venturer|P68|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194403/><ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5605711|shipname=Thor |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 March==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=3 March 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Adriatico''\n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was sunk in an Allied air raid on [[Split (city)|Split]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]].<ref name=seekrieg194403/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Akashishan Maru||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] east of the [[Kuril Islands]] by {{USS|Sand Lance|SS-381|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of 44 lives.<ref name=seekrieg194403/><ref name=Mitsui>{{cite web |url=http://www.theshipslist.com/ships/lines/mitsui.shtml |title=Mitsui company |publisher=www.theshipslist.com |accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Belorussia||2}}\n|flag={{flag|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The timber carrier was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Sea of Okhotsk]] ({{coord|46|28|N|149|18|E}}) by {{USS|Sand Lance|SS-381|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Her [[Sea captain|master]] and 39 crew were killed. There were two survivors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/USN-Chron/USN-Chron-1944.html |title=Official Cronology of the US Navy in WWII |publisher=Ibiblio |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Fort McLeod||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Fort ship]] was torpedoed, shelled and sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] ({{coord|2|01|N|77|06|E}}) by {{ship|Japanese submarine|I-162||2}} ({{navy|Empire of Japan}}). Her crew were rescued by {{HMS|Sluna}} ({{navy|UK}}) and [[tugboat|tug]] {{SS|Integrity||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}).<ref name=FortKS>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/FORT_K.html |title=Fort Ships K-S |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese submarine chaser|Karatsu||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[gunboat]] was torpedoed and damaged off the Philippines by {{USS|Narwhal|SS-167|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Although towed to [[Manila]] for repairs, these were not completed. She was scuttled as a blockship in [[Manila Bay]] on 5 February 1945.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCS(M) 69}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[landing craft support (mortar)]] sank during exercises off east Scotland.<ref name=\"Navypedia\">{{cite web |url= http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lcalcsm.htm |title=LCA Assault Landing Craft and LCS(M) Support Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=2 March 2017}}</ref>><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW2BritishLossesbyDate3.htm |title=Royal Navy vessels lost at sea Jan. '44-Nov. 45 |publisher=Navalhistory.net |accessdate=11 March 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Nittai Maru||2}}\n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Celebes Sea]] {{convert|290|nmi|km}} north west of [[Halmahera]], [[New Guinea]] ({{coord|03|08|N|123|56|E}}) by {{USS|Rasher|SS-269|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). A crewman was killed.<ref name=seekrieg194403/><ref name=Rasher>{{cite DANFS | title = Rasher | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss269.htm | accessdate = 4 January 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese minelayer|Shirakami||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=The {{sclass-|Sokuten|minelayer|||1938}} collided with {{ship||Nichiran Maru}} ({{army|Empire of Japan}}) off [[Yoshino-hama]] in the [[Pacific Ocean]] ({{coord|46|11|N|150|30|E}}) in a storm. Damage control failed and she broke up and sank on 5 March ({{coord|45|30|N|150|00|E}}). Seventy survivors were rescued.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Shirakami_t.htm |title=Japanese Minelayers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 March==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 March 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Anna Martini||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was sunk in an Allied air raid on [[Zadar|Zara]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]].<ref name=seekrieg194403/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck l