6}}, {{HMS|Exmoor|L08|6}} (all {{navy|UK}}) and {{USS|Madison|DD-425|6}} ({{navy|United States|1912}}). All 42 crew survived.<ref name=U450>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u450.htm |title=U-450 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-625||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[File:U-625 sinkt.jpg|thumb|''U-625'']]\nWorld War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the [[Bay of Biscay]] ({{coord|52|35|N|20|19|W}}) by a [[Short Sunderland]] aircraft of [[No. 422 Squadron RCAF|422 Squadron]], [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] with the loss of all 52 crew.<ref name=U625>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u625.htm |title=U-625 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-845||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXC/40]] [[submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|48|20|N|20|33|W}}) by {{HMS|Forester|H74|6}} ({{navy|UK}}), {{HMCS|Owen Sound|K340|6}}, {{HMCS|St. Laurent|H83|6}} and {{HMCS|Swansea|K328|6}} (all {{navy|Canada|1911}}) with the loss of ten of her 55 crew.<ref name=U845>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u845.htm |title=U-845 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|William B. Woods||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed and damaged in the Mediterranean Sea off [[Palermo]], [[Sicily]], Italy ({{coord|38|36|N|13|54|E}}) by {{GS|U-952||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 52 of the 478 people on board. Survivors were rescued by {{ship|Italian torpedo boat|Aretusa||2}} ({{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}) and two [[Fairmile B motor launch]]es ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=LibW>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsW.html |title=Liberty Ships - W |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=WBW>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3217.html |title=William B. Woods |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==11 March==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=11 March 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Andr\u00e9 Lebon''\n|flag={{flagicon|France}} [[Vichy France]]\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[Lighter (barge)|barge]] was bombed and sunk in an American air raid on [[Toulon]], [[Var (department)|Var]].<ref name=seekrieg194403/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Carmen|1925|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk in an American air raid on Toulon.<ref name=seekrieg194403/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship= {{ship|French cruiser|Dupleix|1930|2}}\n|flag={{navy|France}}\n|desc=World War II: The forward half of {{sclass-|Suffren|cruiser|0}} [[heavy cruiser]], which had been salvaged in two halves in 1943, was sunk in an American air raid on Toulon. The stern half sank four days later.<ref name=seekrieg194403/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 884D||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[F-lighter|MFP-D landing craft]] was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_mfp.htm |title=MFP landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|F 888D||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[F-lighter|MFP-D landing craft]] was sunk on this date.<ref name=\"MFP landing craft, Germany\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_mfp.htm |title=MFP landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|M 6000 Altino||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The auxiliary minesweeper was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_conc_patrol.htm |title=Auxiliary Guard ships and Minesweepers of WWII, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|M 6024||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The minesweeper, a former ''Crabe''-class naval tugboat, was bombed and sunk at [[Toulon]] by Allied aircraft.<ref>{{cite web | title=Crabe class patrol tugs (1918-1920), France |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/france/fr_es_crabe.htm |publisher=Navypedia | accessdate=13 April 2017 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|UIT-22||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Liuzzi|submarine}} was bombed and sunk in the [[South Atlantic]] south of the [[Cape of Good Hope]], [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]] ({{Coord|41|28|S|17|40|E}}) by [[South African Air Force]] aircraft with the loss of all 43 crew.<ref name=UIT22>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/uit22.htm |title=UIT-22 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-380||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was sunk at Toulon in an American air raid with the loss of one life.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-410||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was bombed and sunk at Toulon in an American air raid. }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==12 March==\n::''For the sinking of ''Sansei Maru'' on this date see the entry for [[List of shipwrecks in December 1943#8 December|8 December 1943]].\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=12 March 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kilissi||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[banana boat (ship)|banana boat]] was sunk off the mouth of the [[Ebro]] by [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft. Ten crewmen were killed.<ref name=Times140344>{{Cite