ry.net/xDKCas1944-03MAR.htm |title=RN Casualties March 1944 |publisher=www.naval-history.net |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R-161||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[R boat|Type R-151 minesweeper]] was sunk at [[Livorno]], Italy by [[soviet Union|Soviet]] aircraft.<ref name=\"Warshipsww2.Eu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=764 |title=German coastal minesweeper Type R-218 |publisher=Warshipsww2.Eu |accessdate=11 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513030230/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=764 |archive-date=13 May 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Ruth Geiss||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[coastal trading vessel|coaster]] struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Baltic Sea]] off [[Swinem\u00fcnde]].<ref name=seekrieg194403/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German siebel ferry|SF 192||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[Siebel ferry]] was lost on this date.<ref name=\"ReferenceF\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_sf40.htm |title=Siebelfahre 40 and Siebelfahre 41, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German siebel ferry|SF 276||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[Siebel ferry]] was lost on this date.<ref name=\"ReferenceF\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_sf40.htm |title=Siebelfahre 40 and Siebelfahre 41, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Strauss||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a mine and sank in the [[Bay of Kiel]].<ref name=seekrieg194403/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-653||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was torpedoed and sunk by a [[Fairey Swordfish]] of {{HMS|Vindex|D15|6}} and by gunfire from {{HMS|Starling|U66|6}} and {{HMS|Wild Goose|U45|6}} (all {{navy|UK}}).\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 722 Pilote XIII||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Vorpostenboot]]'' struck a mine and sank off [[Brest, France]]. 24 crew were lost.<ref name=seekrieg194403/><ref name=WarDiary4403>{{cite book|title=War Diary German Naval Staff Operations Division March 1944}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German guard ship|Vs 54 Burg||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[guard ship]] struck a mine and sank in the Baltic Sea off [[Fehmarn]]. The crew was rescued.<ref name=seekrieg194403/><ref name=WarDiary4403/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==16 March==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=16 March 1944 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Anzan Maru||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedoed]] and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] by {{USS|Flying Fish|SS-229|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Six crew were killed.<ref name=seekrieg194403/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/CH-49_t.htm |title=Ch-49 |publisher=www.combinedfleet.com |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|El Madina||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo liner]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] by {{Jsub|Ro-111||2}} ({{navy|Empire of Japan}}). 10 crew, 6 gunners and 364 troops died. The British-flagged Norwegian steamer Lovstad rescued the 814 survivors.<ref name=seekrieg194403/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/RO-111.htm |title=RO-111 |publisher=www.combinedfleet.com |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bookofremembrance.islington.gov.uk/BookOfRemembrance/EventFolder.aspx?id=8987 |ti